        "# Data Preprocessing and Feature Engineering for Machine Learning\n",
        "\n",
        "## Aim\n",
        "\n",
        "To implement data preprocessing, feature scaling, feature extraction, dimensional transformation, feature importance, and feature selection techniques to improve data quality, model readiness, and predictive performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Theory\n",
        "\n",
        "## 1. Data Preprocessing\n",
        "\n",
        "Data preprocessing is the process of converting raw data into a clean and suitable format before training a machine learning model.\n",
        "\n",
        "Real-world datasets may contain:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Missing or invalid values\n",
        "- Features with different numerical scales\n",
        "- Skewed data distributions\n",
        "- Irrelevant or redundant features\n",
        "- High-dimensional data\n",
        "\n",
        "Proper preprocessing improves data quality, training efficiency, and model performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "The main preprocessing techniques used in this experiment are:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Handling missing values\n",
        "- Normalization\n",
        "- Standardization\n",
        "- Data transformation\n",
        "- Feature scaling\n",
        "- Feature extraction\n",
        "- Dimensional transformation\n",
        "- Feature importance\n",
        "- Feature selection\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2. Handling Missing Values\n",
        "\n",
        "Missing values occur when valid information is unavailable for some observations. They may be represented as `NaN`, `NULL`, empty cells, or invalid values.\n",
        "\n",
        "In medical datasets, zero may represent an invalid measurement for features such as:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Glucose\n",
        "- Blood Pressure\n",
        "- Skin Thickness\n",
        "- Insulin\n",
        "- BMI\n",
        "\n",
        "Common methods for handling missing values are:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Mean Imputation:** Replaces missing numerical values with the average value.\n",
        "- **Median Imputation:** Replaces missing values with the middle value and is useful when data contains outliers.\n",
        "- **Mode Imputation:** Replaces missing values with the most frequent value and is commonly used for categorical data.\n",
        "\n",
        "The mean is calculated as:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\bar{x} = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_i\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $\\bar{x}$ is the mean value.\n",
        "- $x_i$ represents each observed value.\n",
        "- $n$ is the number of valid observations.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, invalid zero values are converted into missing values and handled using **mean imputation**.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Normalization\n",
        "\n",
        "Normalization transforms numerical features into a fixed range, usually between `0` and `1`.\n",
        "\n",
        "It is also known as **Min-Max Scaling**.\n",
        "\n",
        "The formula is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "x' = \\frac{x-x_{min}}{x_{max}-x_{min}}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $x$ is the original value.\n",
        "- $x_{min}$ is the minimum value.\n",
        "- $x_{max}$ is the maximum value.\n",
        "- $x'$ is the normalized value.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Advantages\n",
        "\n",
        "- Brings features into a common range.\n",
        "- Prevents large-valued features from dominating smaller-valued features.\n",
        "- Useful for distance-based machine learning algorithms.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, normalization is performed using `MinMaxScaler`.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 4. Standardization\n",
        "\n",
        "Standardization transforms numerical features so that they have approximately:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Mean = `0`\n",
        "- Standard deviation = `1`\n",
        "\n",
        "It is also known as **Z-score Scaling**.\n",
        "\n",
        "The formula is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z = \\frac{x-\\mu}{\\sigma}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $x$ is the original value.\n",
        "- $\\mu$ is the mean.\n",
        "- $\\sigma$ is the standard deviation.\n",
        "- $z$ is the standardized value.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Advantages\n",
        "\n",
        "- Centers features around zero.\n",
        "- Reduces the effect of different measurement units.\n",
        "- Makes features comparable.\n",
        "- Important before applying PCA.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, standardization is performed using `StandardScaler`.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 5. Data Transformation\n",
        "\n",
        "Data transformation converts numerical data into a more suitable form for machine learning.\n",
        "\n",
        "It is mainly used to:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Reduce skewness.\n",
        "- Reduce the effect of large values.\n",
        "- Improve data distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "A common technique is **logarithmic transformation**:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "x' = \\log(1+x)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The value `1` is added to avoid calculating the logarithm of zero.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Advantages\n",
        "\n",
        "- Compresses large values.\n",
        "- Reduces positive skewness.\n",
        "- Reduces the influence of extreme values.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, logarithmic transformation is performed using `numpy.log1p()`.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6. Feature Scaling\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature scaling transforms numerical features so that they have comparable magnitudes.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Age may range from `20` to `80`.\n",
        "- Income may range from `20,000` to `1,000,000`.\n",
        "\n",
        "Without scaling, features with larger numerical values may dominate model calculations.\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature scaling is important for algorithms based on:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Distance calculations\n",
        "- Gradient descent\n",
        "- Variance\n",
        "- Principal Component Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "Common feature scaling methods include:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Min-Max Scaling\n",
        "- Standard Scaling\n",
        "- Robust Scaling\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, `StandardScaler` is used for feature scaling.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 7. Dimensionality Reduction\n",
        "\n",
        "Dimensionality reduction is the process of reducing the number of input features while preserving important information.\n",
        "\n",
        "High-dimensional datasets may cause:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Increased computational cost\n",
        "- Model overfitting\n",
        "- Redundant information\n",
        "- Difficulty in visualization\n",
        "- The curse of dimensionality\n",
        "\n",
        "There are two major approaches to dimensionality reduction:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Feature Selection\n",
        "2. Feature Extraction\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8. Feature Selection\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature selection selects the most relevant features from the original dataset and removes irrelevant or redundant features.\n",
        "\n",
        "The original features are not changed. Only the most useful features are retained.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, if the original dataset contains:\n",
        "\n",
        "`Age, Glucose, BMI, Blood Pressure, Insulin`\n",
        "\n",
        "a feature selection method may select:\n",
        "\n",
        "`Glucose, BMI, Age`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Benefits of Feature Selection\n",
        "\n",
        "- Removes irrelevant and redundant features.\n",
        "- Reduces model complexity.\n",
        "- Reduces training time.\n",
        "- Improves model interpretability.\n",
        "- May reduce overfitting.\n",
        "- May improve predictive performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "Common feature selection methods include:\n",
        "\n",
        "- SelectKBest\n",
        "- Chi-Square Test\n",
        "- Correlation-based selection\n",
        "- Recursive Feature Elimination\n",
        "- Feature importance-based selection\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, `SelectKBest` with the Chi-Square test is used to select the top five features.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9. Feature Extraction\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature extraction transforms the original features into a new set of features while preserving important information.\n",
        "\n",
        "Unlike feature selection, feature extraction does not retain the original features. It creates new features by combining information from the original variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example:\n",
        "\n",
        "`Feature 1, Feature 2, Feature 3, ..., Feature 60`\n",
        "\n",
        "may be transformed into:\n",
        "\n",
        "`PC1, PC2, PC3, ..., PC10`\n",
        "\n",
        "where `PC1` to `PC10` are new principal components.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Benefits of Feature Extraction\n",
        "\n",
        "- Reduces the number of dimensions.\n",
        "- Removes redundant information.\n",
        "- Reduces computational complexity.\n",
        "- Helps process high-dimensional datasets.\n",
        "- May reduce model overfitting.\n",
        "\n",
        "Common feature extraction techniques include:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Principal Component Analysis\n",
        "- Linear Discriminant Analysis\n",
        "- Autoencoders\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, PCA is used as a feature extraction technique to transform the 60 original Sonar features into 10 principal components.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 10. Difference Between Feature Selection and Feature Extraction\n",
        "\n",
        "| Property | Feature Selection | Feature Extraction |\n",
        "|---|---|---|\n",
        "| Purpose | Select important original features | Create new transformed features |\n",
        "| Original Features | Preserved | Not preserved |\n",
        "| Output | Subset of original features | New features |\n",
        "| Interpretability | High | Lower |\n",
        "| Example | SelectKBest | PCA |\n",
        "| Used in This Experiment | Task 3 | Task 2 |\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 11. Dimensional Transformation\n",
        "\n",
        "Dimensional transformation converts a high-dimensional dataset into a lower-dimensional representation.\n",
        "\n",
        "The purpose is to:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Reduce the number of features.\n",
        "- Remove redundant information.\n",
        "- Reduce computational complexity.\n",
        "- Improve model readiness.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, dimensional transformation is performed using **Principal Component Analysis**.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12. Principal Component Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "Principal Component Analysis, commonly called **PCA**, is an unsupervised feature extraction and dimensionality reduction technique.\n",
        "\n",
        "PCA transforms the original correlated features into a smaller set of new uncorrelated features called **principal components**.\n",
        "\n",
        "The principal components are ordered according to the amount of variance they preserve:\n",
        "\n",
        "- The first principal component captures the maximum variance.\n",
        "- The second principal component captures the next highest variance.\n",
        "- The remaining components capture decreasing amounts of variance.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Main Steps of PCA\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Standardize the dataset.\n",
        "2. Analyze relationships between features.\n",
        "3. Identify directions containing maximum variance.\n",
        "4. Select the most important principal components.\n",
        "5. Transform the original data into a lower-dimensional form.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Advantages\n",
        "\n",
        "- Reduces the number of features.\n",
        "- Removes redundant information.\n",
        "- Reduces computational complexity.\n",
        "- Helps handle high-dimensional data.\n",
        "- May reduce model overfitting.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, PCA reduces the 60 original features of the Sonar Dataset to 10 principal components.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 13. Explained Variance\n",
        "\n",
        "Explained variance indicates how much information is retained by each principal component.\n",
        "\n",
        "The explained variance ratio is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Explained\\ Variance\\ Ratio =\n",
        "\\frac{\\lambda_i}\n",
        "{\\sum_{j=1}^{n}\\lambda_j}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $\\lambda_i$ is the variance captured by a principal component.\n",
        "- The denominator represents the total variance.\n",
        "\n",
        "A higher explained variance ratio indicates that the principal component preserves more information from the original dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14. Feature Importance\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature importance measures how strongly each input feature contributes to the predictions of a machine learning model.\n",
        "\n",
        "It helps identify:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Important features\n",
        "- Irrelevant features\n",
        "- Features that strongly influence the target variable\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature importance is useful for:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Understanding model behavior.\n",
        "- Ranking input features.\n",
        "- Removing irrelevant features.\n",
        "- Supporting feature selection.\n",
        "- Improving model interpretability.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, feature importance is evaluated using a **Random Forest Classifier**.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 15. Random Forest Feature Importance\n",
        "\n",
        "Random Forest is an ensemble learning algorithm consisting of multiple decision trees.\n",
        "\n",
        "Each tree makes decisions using different subsets of data and features. The predictions of multiple trees are combined to produce the final result.\n",
        "\n",
        "Random Forest calculates feature importance based on how much each feature contributes to useful decision splits.\n",
        "\n",
        "A higher importance score indicates that the feature contributes more strongly to prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Advantages\n",
        "\n",
        "- Identifies influential features.\n",
        "- Captures non-linear relationships.\n",
        "- Supports feature ranking.\n",
        "- Helps remove less useful features.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 16. SelectKBest\n",
        "\n",
        "`SelectKBest` is a filter-based feature selection technique that selects the top `K` features according to a statistical score.\n",
        "\n",
        "The procedure is:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Calculate a statistical score for each feature.\n",
        "2. Rank the features according to their scores.\n",
        "3. Select the top `K` features.\n",
        "\n",
        "Common scoring methods include:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Chi-Square\n",
        "- ANOVA F-test\n",
        "- Mutual Information\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, the top five features are selected using `SelectKBest`.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 17. Chi-Square Feature Selection\n",
        "\n",
        "The Chi-Square test measures the relationship between input features and the target variable.\n",
        "\n",
        "The formula is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\chi^2 =\n",
        "\\sum\n",
        "\\frac{(O-E)^2}{E}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $O$ is the observed value.\n",
        "- $E$ is the expected value.\n",
        "\n",
        "A higher Chi-Square score indicates a stronger relationship between the feature and the target variable.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Note:** Chi-Square feature selection requires non-negative feature values.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this experiment, the Chi-Square test is used with `SelectKBest` to select the top five features.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 18. Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset\n",
        "\n",
